# Check if a Number is a Power of 2

## Formula

```java
(n > 0) && ((n & (n - 1)) == 0)
```

---

## Main Idea

A Power of 2 has **exactly one set bit (1)**.

Examples:

```text
1  = 0001
2  = 0010
4  = 0100
8  = 1000
16 = 10000
32 = 100000
```

Observation:

```text
Power of 2
     ↓
Only one bit is 1
```

---

## Why Does It Work?

When we subtract 1 from a Power of 2:

```text
8  = 1000
7  = 0111
```

Now perform AND:

```text
1000
0111
----
0000
```

Result becomes:

```java
8 & 7 = 0
```

---

## Example 1: n = 8

```text
n     = 1000
n - 1 = 0111
```

```text
1000
0111
----
0000
```

```java
(8 & 7) == 0
```

Output:

```text
true
```

✅ 8 is a Power of 2

---

## Example 2: n = 16

```text
10000
01111
-----
00000
```

Output:

```text
true
```

✅ 16 is a Power of 2

---

## Example 3: n = 10

```text
10 = 1010
 9 = 1001
```

```text
1010
1001
----
1000
```

Result:

```java
(10 & 9) != 0
```

Output:

```text
false
```

❌ 10 is NOT a Power of 2

---

## What Does `n & (n - 1)` Do?

It removes the **rightmost set bit**.

Example:

```text
12 = 1100
11 = 1011
```

```text
1100
1011
----
1000
```

The last `1` is removed.

---

## Why Check `n > 0`?

Without it:

```java
0 & (0 - 1)
```

```text
0 & -1 = 0
```

which would incorrectly return true.

Therefore:

```java
n > 0
```

ensures:

- No zero
- No negative numbers

---

## Java Method

```java
public static boolean isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
    return (n > 0) && ((n & (n - 1)) == 0);
}
```

---

## Time & Space Complexity

| Complexity | Value |
|------------|--------|
| Time | O(1) |
| Space | O(1) |

